TY  - JOUR
T1  - Systems, Boundaries, and Information Flow
AU  - Brown, Warren B.
Y1  - 1966/12/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254950
DO  - 10.5465/254950
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 318
EP  - 327
VL  - 9
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In the attempts to make the study of administration more scientific, one promising technique is the systems analysis approach.1 This has its roots deeply planted in the physical and biological sciences and hence carries with it an aura of respectability. However, its usefulness for the study of human organizations is not yet established, though we certainly can remain optimistic at this point. This paper uses a general systems framework to explore some selected aspects of organizational boundary problems, especially those concerning information flows.
AB  - In the attempts to make the study of administration more scientific, one promising technique is the systems analysis approach.1 This has its roots deeply planted in the physical and biological sciences and hence carries with it an aura of respectability. However, its usefulness for the study of human organizations is not yet established, though we certainly can remain optimistic at this point. This paper uses a general systems framework to explore some selected aspects of organizational boundary problems, especially those concerning information flows.
